interpretations.text: We can see that most districts have a decent immunization coverage close to the target, except for Koinadugo and Kono. Could this be due to low reporting rates as a consequence of their remote locations? There is a significant drop in immunization rates over time - BCG which is given around birth is high but we can observe a coverage drop for penta 3 and measles.

comments.text: Yes it looks live an intervention to improve fully immunized coverage would be needed.

interpretations.text: The District has only one 24/7 facility thus most client deliver outside the district. ANC 1 coverage is high coz women come to pick the nets therefore do not see the importance of 4th ANC. There is relationship between 4 ANC and Deliveries therefore if we embrace community strategy this mothers will be monitored from the start.

comments.text: Most mothers start their ANC profile late in their 3rd trimester and thus do not complete 4 ANC visits before delivery. They do this due to several reasons. One they limit the number of clinic visits to cut on transport cost and save for the unborn child, a small proportion delivers at home due to issues like facility accessibility (lack of night transport) ,peer influence and ignorance, religion and poverty. Almost all live births (home or facility) receive BCG doses. Community strategy approach, OBA and HE at community level and facilities will help cross this gap.

I also concur with the above interpretation. However Mwingi East district has 24 facilities with no District Hospital. There is only one so called sub district hospital with only four maternity beds. So most of deliveries especially if there is any complication are referred to the hospital.

Most mothers start ANC profile late in the 3rd trimester and thus do not complete 4th ANC visit before delivery. Cultural believes contribute to this since communities living in this district believe that delivering in hospital is a taboo. They only visit hospital to confirm that there is no complication before giving birth. On BCG, all children regardless of those born at the hospital or home must be taken for BCG and or are reached through outreaches.

Most mothers start ANC late thus do not complete 4th ANC visit before delivery. Home deliveries are still rampant due to lack of maternity units and poor infrastructure however infants are brought for immunization in the facilities explaining why BCG coverage is high.

interpretations.text: We can see that the drop-out rate in Kenema is very low while Port Loko and Tonkolili have high vales. This might be because the service provision in Kenema is a lot better. We should also investigate potential missing values which drive up the dropout rates.

comments.text: If you drill down to Tonkolili you will see that all chiefdoms have a consistent dropout rate. This indicates that the data might be valid.

interpretations.text: ANC visits has a dip around December - this may be caused by poor reporting rates around the Christmas holiday. ANC 1 coverage is quite high in May 2012, this might be caused by data entry mistakes. Otherwise the trend line indicates that ANC coverage is improving, which may be related to various outreach campaigns country-wide.

comments.text: Note that you can use the data visualizer to drill down on the organisation units to reveal potential sources of data entry mistakes.

interpretations.text: We can see that ANC LLITN coverage is well below the target of 80 percent country-wide. Koinadugo has a suspiciously high value. Might be worthwhile to check out if there is a data entry error causing this.

comments.text: The low LLITN coverage might be caused by lack of nets. We can crosscheck with the number of provided nets to see whether this is a contributing cause.

interpretations.text: We can see clearly that around 1/3 of services are performed outreach. Regarding immunization we see that most children are given vaccines before they reach the age of 1.

We can see that ANC 2 coverage is quite high nationally with values well over 100 percent. This might be real, caused by data entry errors or by wrong data for expected pregnancies. Around 4 percent of the total population is expected to be pregnant every year, we need to investigate if the numbers used are reasonable.
